Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the move "b3b5".

This move shifts our rook from b3 to b5, delivering a check to White’s king on c5. Notice that if White attempts to capture our rook on b5, the bishop on c6 controls that square, so the king cannot simply grab it. This check should help to further restrict the White king and coordinate our winning material advantage.

make_move b3b5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position, one promising option is to give a check with the queen. (Recall: the black queen is on c3 and the white king is on b1. Moving Qc3 to b3 gives check along the b‑file.) 

After Qb3+, if white’s king tries to capture the queen by moving from b1 to b3, that square would be adjacent to our king on c4, which is not allowed for either king. This forces white’s king to move to one of the few safe squares (such as a1 or c1), keeping white under pressure. 

I therefore decide to play:

make_move c3b3

That means if we slide our queen horizontally from g2 to e2, she gives check along the e‐file, and when combined with the bishop’s cover of e2 (and f1) the white king on e1 has no escape square. All neighboring squares are also controlled by our queen (or the bishop), and since white has no other pieces available, this move is checkmate.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play  make_move e3e2 . 

Here's my reasoning: In the current position the white king on f1 only has one safe square (g2) because my queen on e3 covers e1, e2, f2, and g1. By moving my queen from e3 down to e2, I continue to deliver a check (since from e2 the queen directly attacks f1 via the down‐right diagonal) while still covering many of the white king’s escape squares. White’s only reply will be to move the king (most likely to g1), where I can pursue the attack further.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position, one very strong candidate move is to bring your queen out with a checkmate. In our position the queen sits on e2 and the enemy king is on h4. Moving the queen from e2 to g4 places it on a diagonal and vertical line that attacks h4 and covers all of the king’s escape squares. In particular:

• If you move Qe2 to g4, the white king on h4 is in check.
• All adjacent squares around h4—g3, h3, g5, and h5—are also controlled by the queen from g4.

This move leaves the white king with no legal moves, so it is checkmate.

I will now play this move.

make_move e2g4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I notice that Black’s pieces are arranged as follows (interpreting rows from top as rank 8 down to bottom as rank 1):

• Black King is on c5.
• Black Pawn on a5.
• Black Pawn on b4.
• White King is on a4.

One concern is that the Black pawn on b4 is somewhat vulnerable: the enemy king on a4 could capture it if left unprotected. To safeguard that pawn, I want to bring my king closer so that if White tries to capture on b4, it would be illegal (since kings cannot come adjacent). One logical move is to shift the Black king from c5 to c4. From c4, my king will defend the pawn on b4 because b4 becomes adjacent to c4, and capturing it would then force the White king into an illegal adjacency with my king.

Therefore, I will play:

make_move c5c4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current material—a white king on a5, a black pawn on b4, and a black king on c4—here’s how I’ve broken down the position:

• The white king on a5 controls its neighboring squares (a4, a6, b4, b5, and b6); note that although the pawn on b4 is adjacent to the white king, it is defended by the black king on c4 (which covers b4 among other nearby squares), so white cannot capture it without moving into an illegal square.

• The black king on c4 can move one square in any direction, but must avoid squares that would put it adjacent to the white king. Its available moves (in UCI coordinates) are: 
  c4→b3 ("c4b3"), c4→c3 ("c4c3"), c4→d3 ("c4d3"), c4→d4 ("c4d4"), c4→c5 ("c4c5"), and c4→d5 ("c4d5"). 
  (The move c4→b4 isn’t available as that square is occupied by the pawn, and c4→b5 is forbidden because it’s adjacent to white’s king on a5.)

• The black pawn on b4 can advance one square forward (remember that for Black pawns “forward” means toward a lower rank) provided the square is empty. In this case, b4→b3 (“b4b3”) is playable. It also might capture diagonally forward to a3 or c3 if an enemy piece sits there—but here that isn’t the case.

In king-and-pawn endings, king activity is crucial. By centralizing the king, Black can better support the pawn’s advance and limit the white king’s activity. In this position, moving the king to d5 (with “c4d5”) is attractive—it improves Black’s control over critical squares and helps create the conditions to push the pawn later.

Therefore, I will opt to centralize the king with the move:

make_move c4d5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, we have the following placement (using standard algebraic notation with ranks 1–8 from White’s perspective):

 • White king on a4  
 • Black pawn on b3  
 • Black king on c3  

It’s Black’s turn. Reviewing our options:

1. The black king on c3 can move to adjacent squares that aren’t adjacent to the white king. Its legal moves are:  
  – c3 → b2  
  – c3 → c2  
  – c3 → d2  
  – c3 → d3  
  – c3 → d4  
  – c3 → c4  
   (Note: Moves like c3 → b4 are illegal since b4 is adjacent to the white king on a4.)

2. The pawn on b3 can advance forward (for Black, “forward” means to a lower-numbered rank) to b2. Diagonals (a2 or c2) would only be available if there were an opposing piece there, and they are empty.

In king and pawn endgames, supporting your pawn’s advance is the crucial idea—especially when your pawn has a clear path to promotion. Moving your king closer to support the pawn (and eventually force the enemy king away) is a logical plan.

A good move here is to move your king from c3 to d3, thereby stepping closer to the pawn’s path and helping to shepherd it toward promotion.

I will now make that move.

make_move c3d3

To neutralize that threat without having to worry about later tactics (and to clear the way for other pieces), I will relocate the vulnerable rook off that diagonal. Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll analyze the position a bit. One move that immediately catches my eye is using the black knight on d4 to generate some tactical threats. In particular, moving it from d4 to c2 is intriguing because from c2 it creates a fork, attacking the white rook on a1. White will then have to address that threat and, if they move the rook away, Black will win the exchange. (White could attempt to capture the knight with the queen from d1, but that would be awkward since the queen is much more valuable and typically you wouldn’t exchange a queen for a knight.) 

Given this tactical opportunity, I'll proceed with the move:

make_move d4c2
